# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-mechtersheimer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] It later emerged that she had become entangled, as an industry lobbyist, in the CDU donations scandal.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The prosecutors' office in Düsseldorf launched an investigation against her in respect of allegations involving serious fraud, false statements and tax evasion, but by 2007 she was seriously ill and the case was suspended.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] It was dropped in 2008 on account of Hürland-Büning's "permanent incapacity to deal with matters" (*"wegen dauernder Verhandlungsunfähigkeit der Angeklagten"*).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Agnes Oleynik was born into a Roman Catholic family in Holsterhausen, a small town on the western fringes of Dorsten (into which it was formally subsumed in 1943), a mid-sized mining and industrial town north of Essen, a short distance to the east of the Dutch frontier and Nijmegen.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She was enrolled at the local Catholic school in 1932.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] War broke out when she was 13 and troops were stationed at the school: teaching immediately became more "irregular" (*"... sehr unregelmäßig"*), especially after the children were sent to take part in combined classes at one of the two nearby protestant schools.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She completed her schooling young, with others in her cohort, in the spring of 1940, and was conscripted into the Labour Service (*"Reichsarbeitsdienst"*).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She was later sent to work in a munitions factory.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] After war ended, in May 1945, she worked as a volunteer nurse before moving on to complete an apprenticeship as a carer at the "Westfalia Welfare College" (*"Westfälische Wohlfahrtsschule"*) in Münster.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Sources are for the most part silent about her marriage, but by 1960, when she returned to the labour market, it was as Agnes Hürland, the mother of four or five children.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She was employed, till 1968, as a secretary / senior support worker (*"Chefassistentin"*) with an industrial business.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She worked for two years for the national labour agency.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] After that there were two years as a rehabilitation counsellor.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] There are also references to her having worked as an insurance and real-estate broker (*"Immobilienmaklerin"*) during the 1960s and / or early 1970s.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] By 1969 her marriage had ended in divorce: there is a mention of her husband having been affected by alcoholism.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] After a brief flirtation with the centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD) – "because I confused 'social' with 'social democratic'" – Agnes Hürland-Büning joined the centre-right CDU in 1964.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She served as a local councillor in Dorsten between 1969 and 1975, taking a particular interest in social policy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her career as a national politician started only when she was.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her inclusion on the CDU candidate list for North Rhine-Westphalia resulted, according to one unsympathetic source, from the party's introduction of gender quotas.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] As a result, she found herself elected to the Bundestag in 1972.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Nationally the election result was a close one, and many commentators were surprised when, following coalition negotiations, the SPD's Willy Brandt returned to power as Chancellor, while the CDU remained in opposition.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning became a member of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs, in which she took a particular interest in to the needs of the disabled.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Helmut Kohl took over as CDU party leader in 1973.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Apart from her committee work she maintained a low profile in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Kohl nevertheless valued her as a loyal party stalwart and when, in 1982, power finally passed to the CDU, Chancellor Kohl appointed her as "party business leader" (*" Fraktions-Geschäftsführerin"*) in the chamber.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She became known for her humanity, warmth, and willingness to reach out and make informal alliances with members of rival parties.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Even so, evidence of her political impact was limited.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Described by colleagues and observers – sometimes admiringly and sometimes disparagingly – as "the mother of the CDU/CSU party Bundestag group", one underwhelmed commentator suggested that she was at her happiest when organising the annual early summer asparagus lunch for the CDU Bundestag faction.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Directly after the 1987 election Chancellor Kohl made Hürland-Büning his secretary of state for defence.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She had no great specialist knowledge of defence matters, but many felt that her human qualities more than compensated for a lack of technical expertise.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her grandmotherly manner, on display when she visited young recruits and junior officers, provided a reassuring picture.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Indeed, her appointment found support not just within the governing coalition parties but also from the SPD which was the principal opposition party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She was the first woman to hold the post.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She paid particular attention to the welfare of the junior ranks.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] One development that she oversaw was a pilot project for the recruitment of female soldiers (on a volunteer basis).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She continued to enjoy a close political relationship with Helmut Kohl.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] In a prescient remark during a visit to the Knesset in Jerusalem she noted that if anyone could achieve German reunification, it was Helmut Kohl.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Commentators also note that her position within the Ministry of Defence meant that military contracts worth million of marks crossed Agnes Hürland-Büning's desk.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] 1990 was the year of German reunification, and the first general election of the newly unified country took place on 2 December 1990.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] By now approximately six months short of her sixty-fifth birthday, Hürland-Büning did not stand for re-election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She accordingly retired from the Bundestag early in 1991, ahead of the new parliamentary session.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] She retired with her reputation in robust good order, awarded (among other honours) the Order of Merit (*"Große Bundesverdienstkreuz der Bundesrepublik"*) and the Order of Olga.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] However, the name of Agnes Hürland-Büning hit the headlines towards the end of that year in connection with the emerging CDU donations scandal: more details of her alleged involvement in those events, most of which dated back to 1992, appeared in Der Spiegel in January 2000.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning resigned her membership of the Weizsäcker Commission on 20 January 2000, a few days after the Spiegel piece appeared.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her involvement in transferring members of the old East German People's Army to the Bundeswehr was also abruptly terminated when she was dismissed by means of a telephone call from Defences Minister Scharping.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] According to the report of a parliamentary committee of enquiry, after retiring from her position with the Ministry of Defence, Agnes Hürland-Büning concluded several high-value "dubious consultancy agreements".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Just two of the agreements, those with Thyssen AG and Elf Aquitaine, yielded fees amounting to eight and a half or nine and a half million Marks.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] (Sources differ.) What she had to do for all this money never became entirely clear.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] However, investigators felt that this may have amounted, at best, to an incomplete explanation, especially given that eight years later the pipeline construction in question had never taken place, apparently for unrelated reasons.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators appear never fully to have plumbed the suspected depths of the so-called Leuna affair, which sources imply may have been focused not so much on the personal enrichment of top politicians as on the garnering of funds to cover the political expenses incurred by the CDU.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators felt that the massive fees received by Hürland-Büning were completely disproportionate to anything that she might have done to earn them.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] There was also widespread speculation that even if she had received the fees stated, it had never been intended that she should be the ultimate recipient.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The suspicion persisted that she had passed on the funds in the wider context of the Leuna affair and of the associated CDU donations scandal.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] One member of the parliamentary committee was Friedhelm Julius Beucher of the SPD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] He described Hürland-Büning as a "living money-laundering system for the [Christian Democratic] Union (CDU).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] I think the lady's involvement was as the suitcase carrier" (*eine "lebende Geldwaschanlage der Union.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Ich glaube, die Dame war als Kofferträgerin aktiv."*).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] In the words of one commentator, the suspected contents of the suitcase were "black money for Kohl's black coffers" (*"schwarzes Geld für Kohls schwarze Kassen"*).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Nevertheless, it was clear from much of the media comment that many suspected that Hürland-Büning had also enriched herself along the way.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigations by the prosecutors' office were followed by the issuance of charges in December 2003.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Once her consultancy activities had been defined as a business it became liable for substantial arrears of unpaid business tax to the municipality.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] During her final years, with the threat of legal sanctions hanging over her, and a new generation of leaders controlling the CDU, there are indications that Hürland-Büning felt abandoned by those who had previously been friends.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her former mentor Helmut Kohl increasingly withdrew from public life after the CDU donations scandal became public, especially following the tragic death of his first wife in 2001.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Within the little town of Dorsten there emerges a sense, from some sources, that family members and remaining friends felt that the work she had been able to do for individual citizens with problems, for Dorsten businesses, and for the town more generally, were all too quickly forgotten.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Meanwhile, at her criminal trial matters took a new twist in September 2004 when her defence lawyer submitted a doctor's certificate attesting that the 78 year old defendant's deteriorating health meant that she was no longer sufficiently fit to enable a fair trial take place.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Although it would take more than three more years for the court to reach a final decision in respect of the medical evidence, it was becoming increasingly likely that Agnes Hürland-Büning would go to the grave unconvicted but without her name ever being cleared.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] That was indeed the position on 9 March 2009 when she died following a major operation.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Only her family and a small number of close friends were present at her burial.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Her parliamentary colleagues were represented by a wreath that arrived from the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Since then she has been commemorated each year by a further wreath, sent on All Saints' Day, and decorated with the black/red/gold sash of the CDU/CSU, on behalf of her Bundestag former party colleagues and their successors in Berlin.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2011 insolvency proceedings were launched against the estate of Agnes Hürland-Büning in respect of around €200,000 in unpaid business taxes payable to the municipality of Dorsten at the time of her death.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] By 2011 the debt had been reduced to around €170,000 by means of monthly payments of €1,000.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The city maintained its claim for the balance through the bankruptcy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The business tax claim by the municipality had already been the subject of major disagreements within the council as far back as 2002.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] At that point CDU councillors, with their controlling majority, had agreed to a compromise deal with their high-profile debtor, freezing the debt and hoping, by means of the agreement, at least to secure monthly repayments of €1,000.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] SPD and Green Party councillors had opposed the settlement while the FDP councillors had abstained in the vote.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The CDU share of the votes in the local council election slipped below 50% in 2009, although they remained the largest single party, with 22 of the 44 council seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2012, during an interview concerning the state of municipal finances, a reporter asked the Dorsten town treasurer – another CDU councillor – about the prospects of recovering the unpaid business taxes of former CDU Bundestag member Agnes Hürland-Büning.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The treasurer declined to speculate on how much money would become available at the conclusion of the insolvency proceedings.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Bundesautobahn 31 runs parallel with the Dutch frontier, linking Emden in the north with Bottrop to the south.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The section passing to the west of Dorsten was completed and opened in 1989.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Between Junctions 37 and 38 there is an unmarked junction, without signage and without a junction number.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The unmarked junction was not included in the plans for the road, and only those with local knowledge are aware that it can be accessed by leaving or joining the Autobahn where maps and signs indicate a parking area ("Parkplatz Dorsten-Holsterhausen").
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The limited access junction only permits traffic to join the Autobahn in a southerly direction, towards Bottrop (and, indirectly, Bonn) or to leave the Autobahn travelling north (from Bottrop and, indirectly, Bonn).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The rumour gained added traction after the name of the former secretary of state began to appear in press reports connecting her with the CDU donations scandal.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Der Spiegel gave it national coverage in 2000 and repeated it in 2002.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2009 the pupils in class 9a at the Gymnasium St.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Ursula (secondary school) undertook what turned out to be an award winning investigation into the origins of the *"Hürlandausfahrt"*.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Arnold Erwig, their politics teacher, admitted that at the outset he had always assumed the rumours were true.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Only a few were prepared to have their voices recorded.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The town council had indeed objected to the Autobahn plans which had specified a junction at the hamlet of Schembeck, to the north, and a junction at Dorsten-West, some distance to the south.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] The city father demanded an extra Autobahn junction, but without success.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] They then invoked their local representative in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Through her relationship with Chancellor Kohl, it turned out that Agnes Hürland-Büning did enjoy more influence with the transport planners than might have been expected.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Even her lobbying powers were not sufficient to provide for a complete additional junction, but the unmarked junction, accessible through the parking area, represented a compromise for which the city council at the time was appreciative.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/agnes-hürland-büning] Those with the necessary local knowledge were able to save themselves time by using the "secret" junction: at the time that did indeed includes Agnes Hürland-Büning herself.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Probst was born in Garching bei München, Upper Bavaria.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] After graduation in 1951 from the Maximilians Gymnasium in Munich, Probst took an agricultural apprenticeship.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He then studied agricultural sciences at the Technical University of Munich, graduating in 1958 with a diploma as an agricultural engineer.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] In Munich, he served in the Catholic student group K.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He then joined the agricultural civil service, working at the milk research institute at TU Munich.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He left this institute in 1961, after completing research.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He returned to TU Munich in 1963, after two years as an agriculture adviser in France, to work on a research project concerning population genetics.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] At this time he began to participate in municipal politics.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Probst was deputy chair of the culture team of the Christian Socialist Union for many years.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] From 1960 to 1973 he belonged to the country of the circle day of the district of Munich.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He was also a member of the Garching local council from 1966 until 1990.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] From 1969 to 1998 Probst was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He was chair of the Committee on Development and Science from 1972 to 1976, and from 1976 to 1982 chaired the Committee on Research and Technology.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Until 1982, he chaired the science development team and served as spokesperson for the Christian Socialist Union rural group.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Probst was a directly selected delegate of the Munich/Freising constituency in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] From 1991 to 1999 he represented Germany at parliamentary meetings of the Council of Europe, and at the European Union.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] On 4 October 1982 Probst became Parliamentary Secretary of State at the Federal Ministry for Research and Technology, in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Here he advocated the early provision of computers in schools.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] He served until the Bundestag election in 1990, leaving government on 24 January 1991.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/albert-probst] Probst is married and has four children.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] After graduating from a school in Werl, he entered the German Wehrmacht in 1939.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] He was wounded four times and served until the end of the war, when he commanded a battalion on the Eastern Front at the rank of Captain.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] In 1946, he began studying law and government at the universities of Marburg and Tübingen, earning his doctorate in 1950.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] Dregger served from 1956 to 1970 as *Oberbürgermeister* or mayor of Fulda; when first elected, he was the youngest mayor in West Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] He also served from 1962 to 1972 as a member of the Landtag of Hesse.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] He was for a time leader of the CDU in that body, and, in 1967, became state party chairman, an office which he held until 1982.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] In 1969 he was also elected as a member of the national board of the party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] From 1972 1998 he was a representative in the German Bundestag; from 1982 to 1991 he was Chairman of the CDU/CSU group there.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] Dregger was known as a staunch conservative and was a prominent member of the so-called Stahlhelm-Fraktion, a National-Conservative wing of the CDU.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] In the 1970s he was an outspoken proponent of outlawing the German Communist Party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] He was responsible for the slogan "Freiheit statt Sozialismus" (Freedom instead of Socialism) with which the CDU had great success in the 1976 elections.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] In his eulogy, German Chancellor Friedrich Merz said of him, "Few have so clearly and categorically opposed the Left for decades".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] He called for Germany to "come out of Hitler's shadow".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-dregger] Alfred Dregger was married and had two sons; his elder son was killed in an accident in 1972.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] Mechtersheimer was a leading figure in the peace movement in the late 1970s and early 1980s, and one of the founders of the ecopax movement.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] Consequently, Mechtersheimer's political career saw him move from Bavarian CSU to the Greens in the 1980s.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] Later he distanced himself from the Greens as well, for their, he thought, lack of patriotism.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] Afterwards Mechtersheimer organized various movements known for their "stridently nationalist brand of national pacifism".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] He called his politics since the 1990s "Nationalpazifismus" (literary 'National- pacifism').
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alfred-mechtersheimer] Mechtersheimer died on 22 December 2018, at the age of 79.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Since November 2024, Franziska Brantner and Felix Banaszak have been co-leaders of the party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It currently holds 85 of the 630 seats in the Bundestag, having won 11% of first votes and 11.6% of second votes cast in the 2025 federal election, putting it in fourth place of the seven political parties by number of seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its parliamentary co-leaders are Britta Haßelmann and Katharina Dröge.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens have been part of the federal government twice: first as a junior partner to the Social Democrats (SPD) from 1998 to 2005, and then with the SPD and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) in the traffic light coalition from the 2021 election until that coalition's collapse in 2024.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Scholz cabinet, the Greens had five ministers, including Vice-Chancellor Robert Habeck and Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party holds seats in most of Germany's state legislatures, except Saarland, Thuringia and Brandenburg, and is a member of coalition governments in seven states.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Cem Özdemir, Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg, is the only Green head of government in Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Landtag of Baden-Württemberg is also the only state legislature in which Alliance 90/The Greens is the largest party; it is the second largest party in the legislatures of Berlin, Hamburg and Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens is a founding member of the European Green Party and the Greens–European Free Alliance group in the European Parliament.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It is currently the largest party in the G/EFA group, with 21 MEPs.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European election, Alliance 90/The Greens was the second largest party in Germany, winning 20.5% of votes cast.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party had 166,000 members in February 2025, making it the third largest party in Germany by membership.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Green Party was initially founded in West Germany as *Die Grünen* (the Greens) in January 1980.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It grew out of the anti-nuclear energy, environmental, peace, new left, and new social movements of the late 20th century.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Between 1977 and 1979 local parties running on on environmental and peace issues were established across West Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although most environmental and anti-nuclear activists were initially sceptical of these efforts, a lack of results from pressure group activity and early electoral successes meant the approach gained momentum and led to local groups amalgamating into state-level parties.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The West Berlin state branch of The Greens was founded as *Alternative Liste*, or precisely, *Alternative Liste für Demokratie und Umweltschutz* (AL; alternative list for democracy and environmental protection) in 1978 and became the official West Berlin branch of The Greens in 1980.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1993, it renamed to Alliance 90/The Greens Berlin after the merger with East Berlin's Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hamburg state branch of the Green Party was called *Grün-Alternative Liste Hamburg* (GAL; green-alternative list) from its foundation in 1982 until 2012.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1984, it became the official Hamburg branch of The Greens.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In July 1978 former Christian Democrat Herbert Gruhl founded *Grüne Aktion Zukunft* (GAZ - green action future) as the beginning of a process to establish a nationwide green party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In February 1979 an electoral alliance was established to contest the first democratic elections to the European Parliament later that year under the name *Sonstige Politische Vereinigung Die Grünen* (SPV-Die Grünen - alternative political alliance, the greens).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This included GAZ, GLU, *Grüne Liste Schleswig-Holstein* and the Action Group of Independent Germans (a pro-neutrality pacifist political party which had adopted pro-environment policies in the 1970s and was predominantly present in southern Germany).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two members of the BBU's executive, Petra Kelly and Roland Vogt, also joined the alliance, and it was also supported by prominent writer Heinrich Böll and socialist activist Rudi Dutschke.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, not all local green groups supported the coalition, including the West Berlin *Alternative Liste* and the *Bunte Liste* (Multicoloured List) in Hamburg, the latter being a rival green party to the city's GLU branch.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Both of these lists were heavily influenced by the activism of the Communist League.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen ran on a platform advocating a nuclear-free Europe and a Europe of the Regions, and scored 3.2 percent of the vote.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As German electoral law provided for a generous scheme for reimbursement of election expenses, providing them to all parties scoring at least 0.5 percent of the vote, the new formation netted 4.8 million deutschmarks, after spending just 300,000 on its campaign.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This money was spent on establishing state and national party infrastructure.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] SPV-Die Grünen's success led to increased activist interest, with membership rising to around 10,000 by the end of 1979, and the Alternative and Multicoloured Lists showing more interest in joining forces with the other green groups.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A congress in October 1979 to agree a programme for the national party led to heated disagreements over economic orientation and non-violence and whether dual membership with other parties was to be permitted.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the latter was resolved by agreeing to devolve decisions on membership to local branches, the former was overcome by the adoption of what would become known as the four pillars of green politics: ecology, social responsibility, grassroots democracy and non-violence.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Journalist and activist August Haußleiter claimed to have proposed these and secured the agreement of the leaders of the right (Gruhl) and left (Jürgen Reents) factions at the conference.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The nascent movement received a further boost the same month when the *Bremer Grüne Liste* became the first green party to win seats in a state parliament, securing four seats in Bremen's election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The political party **The Greens** (German: *Die Grünen*) sprung out of the wave of New Social Movements that were active in the 1970s, including environmentalist, anti-war, and anti-nuclear movements which can trace their origin to the student protests of 1968.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Officially founded as a German national party on 13 January 1980 in Karlsruhe, the party sought to give these movements political and parliamentary representation, as the pre-existing people's parties were not organised in a way to address their stated issues.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Its membership included organisers from former attempts to achieve institutional representation such as GLU and AUD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Opposition to pollution, use of nuclear power, NATO military action, and certain aspects of industrialised society were principal campaign issues.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also championed sexual liberation and some of their members supported the abolition of age-of-consent laws.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The formation of a party was purportedly first discussed by movement leaders in 1978.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Important figures in the first years were – among others – Petra Kelly, Joschka Fischer, Gert Bastian, Lukas Beckmann, Rudolf Bahro, Joseph Beuys, Antje Vollmer, Herbert Gruhl, August Haußleiter, Luise Rinser, Dirk Schneider, Christian Ströbele, Jutta Ditfurth, Baldur Springmann and Werner Vogel.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1982, the conservative factions of the Greens broke away to form the Ecological Democratic Party (ÖDP).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also tended to identify more closely with a culture of protest and civil disobedience, frequently clashing with police at demonstrations against nuclear weapons, nuclear energy, and the construction of a new runway (*Startbahn West*) at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Those who left the party at the time might have felt similarly about some of these issues, but did not identify with the forms of protest that Green party members took part in.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Among the important political issues at the time was the deployment of Pershing II IRBMs and nuclear-tipped cruise missiles by the U.S. and NATO on West German soil, generating strong opposition in the general population that found an outlet in mass demonstrations.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The newly formed party was able to draw on this popular movement to recruit support.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The state electoral success in Hesse and Hamburg saw the party holding the balance of power in both states.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hamburg the party won nine seats in the June 1982 election and made an offer of terms for confidence and supply to the Social Democrats, but these were rejected.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the following December election the Greens lost a seat and the SPD won an absolute majority.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Hesse the Greens rejected the idea of cooperating with the SPD after the 1982 election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Another state election took place there the following year, resulting in the Greens losing two seats but no party achieving a majority.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the election the state Greens voted to accept a confidence and supply agreement with the Social Democrats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite this negotiations immediately commenced over terms for a coalition agreement.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the party's Bundestag faction had limited success in legislating during the new MPs' first term, they were able to influence debate inside and outside parliament through proposing bills and asking questions.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, the faction's efforts were disrupted by the attempt to implement rotation of members halfway through their terms as had been planned before the 1983 election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] All elected Bundestag members except Petra Kelly stepped down to enable rotation, however of the seven Green MEPs elected in the 1984 European election only three resigned from their roles.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The rotation stipulation was subsequently abolished, however the departure of many Bundestag members who had received significant media attention upon their entry to parliament led to reduced press interest in the parliamentary faction's work.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, elections in 1985 brought mixed results.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Contrastingly, in the West Berlin elections, after the SPD rejected the Alternative List's terms for a confidence and supply agreement before polling day, the SPD scored their worst post-war result of 32.4 percent, whilst the Greens almost doubled their vote to 10.6 percent and took 15 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the SPD won 52.1 percent of the vote, the Greens failed to meet the electoral threshold with 4.6 percent.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile, in local elections in Hesse both the SPD and Greens made gains, with the vote of the latter rising to 7.1 percent.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly after Börner offered a coalition deal to the Greens which included the position of environment and energy minister.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer took up the ministerial post, whilst Marita Haibach was made secretary of state for woman's affairs.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the federal party conference in Offenburg in December, the party's fundi faction, which had been hostile to the coalition agreement, took control of the party's executive.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 1986, the intra-party conflict reduced somewhat.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A party conference in Hanover that Easter voted for an immediate end to nuclear power and the end of the coalition in Hesse.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These attacks limited the party's gains to 0.6 percent of the vote, failing to add to the 11 seats won at the previous state election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, in the Bavarian state election the party entered parliament for the first time, winning 7.5 percent of the vote and 15 seats, whilst in the Hamburg elections an all-female list secured 10.4 percent of votes and 13 seats, whilst neither the CDU or SPD secured a parliamentary majority.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Around this time, Joschka Fischer emerged as the unofficial leader of the party, which he remained until resigning all leadership posts following the 2005 federal election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the federal election, factional tensions over strategy re-emerged.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Hesse party withdrew from their coalition with the SPD, over the same nuclear enrichment plant which had led to the collapse of the previous confidence and supply agreement.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the subsequent 1987 Hessian state election, the SPD vote declined, leading to a coalition of Christian Democrats and Free Democrats entering government, but the Green vote increased to 9.4 percent, securing them 10 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the Hamburg election held to resolve the deadlock resulting from the previous year's poll, the Green vote dropped to 7.1 percent, losing them five seats, whilst the SPD and FDP were able to form a coalition.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Meanwhile in Rhineland-Palatinate the Greens entered parliament for the first time, taking 5.9 percent of the vote and six seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Later that year in state elections in Schleswig-Holstein the state Green party, which was opposed to participating in any coalition, failed to enter parliament and won only 3.9 percent of the vote, whilst in Bremen they almost doubled their vote to 10.2 percent and won ten seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Tensions were further inflamed by the killing of two police officers and injury of nine others by autonomist activists at a protest at Frankfurt Airport.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Whilst the bulk of the party condemned the killings, some on the left including Ditfurth and Thomas Ebermann did not.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The growing disagreements at the federal level resulted in a crisis meeting in December 1987, following by a perspective congress in June 1988.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens were the target of attempts by the East German secret police to enlist the cooperation of members who were willing to align the party with the agenda of the German Democratic Republic.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party ranks included several politicians who were later discovered to have been Stasi agents, including Bundestag representative Dirk Schneider, European Parliament representative Brigitte Heinrich, and Red Army Faction defense lawyer Klaus Croissant.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Greens politician and Bundestag representative Gert Bastian was also a founding member of Generals for Peace, a pacifist group created and funded by the Stasi, the revelation of which may have contributed to the murder-suicide in which he killed his partner and Greens founder Petra Kelly.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A study commissioned by the Greens determined that 15 to 20 members intimately cooperated with the Stasi and another 450 to 500 had been informants.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Until 1987, the Greens included a faction involved in pedophile activism, the *SchwuP* short for *Arbeitsgemeinschaft "Schwule, Päderasten und Transsexuelle"* (approx.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] *working group "Gays, Pederasts and Transsexuals"*).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This faction campaigned for repealing § 176 of the German penal code, dealing with child sexual abuse.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This group was controversial within the party itself, and was seen as partly responsible for the poor election result of 1985.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This controversy re-surfaced in 2013 and chairwoman Claudia Roth stated she welcomed an independent scientific investigation on the extent of influence pedophile activists had on the party in the mid-1980s.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In November 2014, the political scientist Franz Walter presented the final report about his research on a press conference.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1990 federal elections, taking place post-reunified Germany, the Greens in the West did not pass the 5% limit required to win seats in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] It was only due to a temporary modification of German election law, applying the five-percent "hurdle" separately in East and West Germany, that the Greens acquired any parliamentary seats at all.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This happened because in the new states of Germany, the Greens, in a joint effort with Alliance 90, a heterogeneous grouping of civil rights activists, were able to gain more than 5% of the vote.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Some critics attribute this poor performance to the reluctance of the campaign to cater to the prevalent mood of nationalism, instead focusing on subjects such as global warming.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] A campaign poster at the time proudly stated, "Everyone is talking about Germany; we're talking about the weather!", paraphrasing a popular slogan of Deutsche Bundesbahn, the German national railway.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party also opposed imminent reunification that was in process, instead wanting to initiate debates on ecology and nuclear issues before reunification causing a drop in support in Western Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the 1994 federal election; however, the merged party returned to the Bundestag, and the Greens received 7.3% of the vote nationwide and 49 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 1998 federal election, despite a slight fall in their percentage of the vote (6.7%), the Greens retained 47 seats and joined the federal government for the first time in 'Red-Green' coalition government with the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Joschka Fischer became Vice-Chancellor of Germany and foreign minister in the new government, which had two other Green ministers (Andrea Fischer, later Renate Künast, and Jürgen Trittin).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Almost immediately the party was plunged into a crisis by the question of German participation in the NATO actions in Kosovo.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Numerous anti-war party members resigned their party membership when the first post-war deployment of German troops in a military conflict abroad occurred under a Red-Green government, and the party began to experience a long string of defeats in local and state-level elections.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2001, the party experienced a further crisis as some Green Members of Parliament refused to back the government's plan of sending military personnel to help with the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Chancellor Gerhard Schröder called a vote of confidence, tying it to his strategy on the war.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Four Green MPs and one Social Democrat voted against the government, but Schröder was still able to command a majority.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On the other hand, the Greens achieved a major success as a governing party through the 2000 decision to phase out the use of nuclear energy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Minister of Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety Jürgen Trittin reached an agreement with energy companies on the gradual phasing out of the country's nineteen nuclear power plants and a cessation of civil usage of nuclear power by 2020.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was authorised through the Nuclear Exit Law.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Based on an estimate of 32 years as the normal period of operation for a nuclear power plant, the agreement defines precisely how much energy a power plant is allowed to produce before being shut down.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Despite the crises of the preceding electoral period, in the 2002 federal election, the Greens increased their total to 55 seats (in a smaller parliament) and 8.6%.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens benefited from increased inroads among traditionally left-wing demographics which had benefited from Green-initiated legislation in the 1998–2002 term, such as environmentalists (Renewable Energies Act) and LGBT groups (Registered Partnership Law).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Perhaps most important for determining the success of both the Greens and the SPD was the increasing threat of war in Iraq, which was highly unpopular with the German public, and helped gather votes for the parties which had taken a stand against participation in this war.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] One internal issue in 2002 was the failed attempt to settle a long-standing discussion about the question of whether members of parliament should be allowed to become members of the party executive.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Two party conventions declined to change the party statute.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The necessary majority of two-thirds was missed by a small margin.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] As a result, former party chairpersons Fritz Kuhn and Claudia Roth (who had been elected to parliament that year) were no longer able to continue in their executive function and were replaced by former party secretary general Reinhard Bütikofer and former Bundestag member Angelika Beer.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party then held a member referendum on this question in the spring of 2003 which changed the party statute.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Now members of parliament may be elected for two of the six seats of the party executive, as long as they are not ministers or caucus leaders.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] 57% of all party members voted in the member referendum, with 67% voting in favor of the change.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The referendum was only the second in the history of Alliance 90/The Greens, the first having been held about the merger of the Greens and Alliance 90.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In 2004, after Angelika Beer was elected to the European Parliament, Claudia Roth was elected to replace her as party chair.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 party convention was held in Dresden and decided the election platform for the 2004 European Parliament elections.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The German Green list for these elections was headed by Rebecca Harms (then leader of the Green party in Lower Saxony) and Daniel Cohn-Bendit, previously Member of the European Parliament for The Greens of France.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The November 2003 convention is also noteworthy because it was the first convention of a German political party ever to use an electronic voting system.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens gained a record 13 of Germany's 99 seats in these elections, mainly due to the perceived competence of Green ministers in the federal government and the unpopularity of the Social Democratic Party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In early 2005, the Greens were the target of the German Visa Affair 2005, instigated in the media by the Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the end of April 2005, they celebrated the decommissioning of the Obrigheim nuclear power station.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They also continue to support a bill for an Anti-Discrimination Law (Allgemeines Gleichbehandlungsgesetz) in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In May 2005, the only remaining state-level red-green coalition government lost the vote in the North Rhine-Westphalia state election, leaving only the federal government with participation of the Greens (apart from local governments).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the early 2005 federal election the party incurred very small losses and achieved 8.1% of the vote and 51 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] However, due to larger losses of the SPD, the previous coalition no longer had a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] For almost two years after the federal election in 2005, the Greens were not part of any government at the state or federal level.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2007, the Greens in Bremen entered into a coalition with the Social Democratic Party (SPD) following the 2007 Bremen state election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In April 2008, following the 2008 Hamburg state election, the Green-Alternative List (GAL) in Hamburg entered into a coalition with the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), the first such state-level coalition in Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Although the GAL had to agree to the deepening of the Elbe River, the construction of a new coal-fired power station and two road projects they had opposed, they also received some significant concessions from the CDU.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] These included reforming state schools by increasing the number of primary school educational stages, the restoration of trams as public transportation in the city-state, and more pedestrian-friendly real estate development.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] On 29 November 2010, the coalition collapsed, resulting in an election that was won by SPD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Following the Saarland state election of August 2009, The Greens held the balance of power after a close election where no two-party coalitions could create a stable majority government.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In June 2010, in the first state election following the victory of the CDU/CSU and FDP in the 2009 federal election, the "black-yellow" CDU-FDP coalition in North Rhine-Westphalia under Jürgen Rüttgers lost its majority.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] So a red-green government in a state where it was defeated under Peer Steinbrück in 2005 came into office again on 14 June 2010 with the election of Hannelore Kraft as minister-president (Cabinet Kraft I).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens founded the first international chapter of a German political party in the U.S. on 13 April 2008 at the Goethe-Institut in Washington D.C.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2011 (two weeks after the Fukushima nuclear disaster had begun), the Greens made large gains in Rhineland-Palatinate and in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In Baden-Württemberg they became the senior partner in a governing coalition for the first time.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Winfried Kretschmann is now the first Green to serve as Minister-President of a German State (Cabinet Kretschmann I and II).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Polling data from August 2011 indicated that one in five Germans supported the Greens.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] From 4 October 2011 to 4 September 2016, the party was represented in all state parliaments.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Like the Social Democrats, the Greens backed Chancellor Angela Merkel on most bailout votes in the German parliament during her second term, saying their pro-European stances overrode party politics.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Shortly before the elections, the party plummeted to a four-year low in the polls, undermining efforts by Peer Steinbrück's Social Democrats to unseat Merkel.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] While being in opposition on the federal level since 2005, the Greens have established themselves as a powerful force in Germany's political system.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] By 2016, the Greens had joined 11 out of 16 state governments in a variety of coalitions.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Over the years, they have built up an informal structure called G-coordination to organize interests between the federal party office, the parliamentary group in the Bundestag, and the Greens governing on the state level.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens remained the smallest of six parties in the Bundestag in the 2017 federal election, winning 8.9% of votes.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the election, they entered into talks for a Jamaica coalition with the CDU and FDP.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Discussions collapsed after the FDP withdrew in November.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] After the federal election and unsuccessful Jamaica negotiations, the party held elections for two new co-leaders; incumbents Özdemir and Peter did not stand for re-election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Robert Habeck and Annalena Baerbock were elected with 81% and 64% of votes, respectively.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Habeck had served as deputy premier and environment minister in Schleswig-Holstein since 2012, while Baerbock had been a leading figure in the party's Brandenburg branch since 2009.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Their election was considered a break with tradition, as they were both members of the moderate wing.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens saw a major surge in support during the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October 2018, becoming the second largest party in both.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They subsequently rose to second place behind the CDU/CSU in national polling, averaging between 17% and 20% over the next six months.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the 2019 European Parliament election, the Greens achieved their best ever result in a national election, placing second with 20.5% of the vote and winning 21 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] National polling released after the election showed a major boost for the party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The first poll after the election, conducted by Forsa, showed the Greens in first place on 27%.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This was the first time the Greens had ever been in first place in a national opinion poll, and the first time in the history of the Federal Republic that any party other than the CDU/CSU or SPD had placed first in a national poll.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] This trend continued as polls from May to July showed the CDU/CSU and Greens trading first place, after which point the CDU/CSU pulled ahead once more.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens continued to poll in the low 20% range into early 2020.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens recorded best-ever results in the Brandenburg (10.8%) and Saxony (8.6%) state elections in September 2019, and subsequently joined coalition governments in both states.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They suffered an unexpected decline in the Thuringian election in October, only narrowing retaining their seats with 5.2%.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the February 2020 Hamburg state election, the Greens became the second largest party, winning 24.2% of votes cast.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In March 2021, the Greens improved their performance in Baden-Württemberg, where they remained the strongest party with 32.6% of votes, and Rhineland-Palatinate, where they moved into third place with 9.3%.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Due to their sustained position as the second most popular party in national polling ahead of the September 2021 federal election, the Greens chose to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single Chancellor candidate.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Co-leader Annalena Baerbock was announced as Chancellor candidate on 19 April and formally confirmed on 12 June with 98.5% approval.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens surged in opinion polls in late April and May, briefly surpassing the CDU as the most popular party in the country, but their numbers slipped back after Baerbock was caught up in several controversies.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Her personal popularity also fell below that of both Armin Laschet and Olaf Scholz, the Chancellor candidates for the CDU and SPD, respectively.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party's fortunes did not reverse even after the July floods, which saw climate change return as the most important issue among voters.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The situation worsened in August as the SPD surged into first place to the detriment of both the CDU and Greens.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens finished in third place in the 2021 federal election with 14.8% of votes.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Though their best ever federal election result, it was considered a bitter disappointment in light of their polling numbers during the previous three years.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] They entered coalition talks with the FDP and SPD, eventually joining a traffic light coalition under Chancellor Olaf Scholz which took office on 8 December 2021.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens have five ministers in the Scholz cabinet, including Robert Habeck as Vice-Chancellor and Annalena Baerbock as foreign minister.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Since party statute mandates that party leaders may not hold government office, Baerbock and Habeck stepped down after entering cabinet.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At a party conference in January 2022, Ricarda Lang and Omid Nouripour were elected to succeed them.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] At the time of her election, Lang was 28 years old, speaker for women's issues, and a former leader of the Green Youth.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] 46-year-old Nouripour was foreign affairs spokesman and a member of the Bundestag since 2006.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Of the new leaders, Lang is considered a representative of the party's left-wing, while Nouripour represents the right-wing.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Lang and Nouripour announced their resignations as party leaders in September 2024 after heavy defeats in the Saxony, Thuringia and Brandenburg state elections that month, as well as the earlier European Parliament election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In all three states, governing coalitions involving the Greens were not returned, and the party was wiped out in the latter two states while only narrowly retaining representation in Saxony.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] In the European elections, the Greens fell to fourth (behind the CDU/CSU, AfD and SPD) and lost 9 seats in the European parliament, falling to 12 seats.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party had fallen out of five state governments (additionally Berlin and Hesse) since entering the federal governing coalition in 2021.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Analysts pointed to its participation in the federal government requiring it to take stances that are contrary to its traditional clean-energy and pacifist ideals, as well as a stark collapse in support with young voters.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] Felix Banaszak and Franziska Brantner elected as co-leaders in November 2024.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] During the 2024 government crisis, in which the FDP left the traffic light coalition, the Greens stayed in a red-green minority coalition.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party abstained in the succeeding vote of no confidence, ensuring the government's collapse and the calling of the 2025 federal election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The party chose incumbent Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck as their chancellor candidate for the 2025 federal election.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The Greens would go on to lose 33 seats in that election, garnering 11.6% of the vote.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The unpopularity of the Scholz cabinet has been credited with the result, although this was still the party's second best ever result.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The morning after the election, Habeck announced his withdrawal from the party's leadership.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p01] The other co-candidate for The Greens, Annalena Baerbock, as well as former party leader Ricarda Lang, were expected to become the next party leaders in the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party's main ideological trends are green politics and social liberalism.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has also been described as left-libertarian, and influenced by the postmaterialist left.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party's political position is generally described to be centre-left, while others describe the party as centrist or left-wing.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens originated as a left-wing protest party in the 1980s but have since evolved into a centre-left party, especially after merging with Alliance 90 in 1993.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The West German Greens played a crucial role in the development of green politics in Europe, with their original program outlining "four principles: ecological, social, grassroots, and non-violent".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Initially ideologically heterogenous, the party took up a position on the radical left in its early years, which were dominated by conflicts between the more left-wing *Fundi* (fundamentalist) and more moderate *Realo* (realist) factions.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Writing in the late 1980s, Sara Parkin characterised the factional divides in the party as occurring along three axes: the strategic divide between fundis and realos, the left–right political spectrum, and the existence of affinity groups.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] From this view, watering down a radical worldview risked a failure to take sufficiently drastic action in the face of environmental crisis.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] As Kelly put it, "It does not help us in any way if we begin accepting lower and safer levels of, for example, radioactivity...
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] We must speak out clear, loudly and courageously, if we know there are no safe levels".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Fundis also express concern about losing touch with grassroots activists, and in Germany particularly emphasise solidarity with groups they consider to be victimised by the state, resulting in them being less likely to condemn use of violence by protest movements than realos.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to Parkin, fundis were particularly prevalent on state and federal committees and executive bodies and formed a minority in parliamentary parties.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Realos are reformists who argue that the appropriate response to ecological crisis is to take action within the existing political system, and that to do otherwise is to condemn the green movement to irrelevance.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They stress the importance of going beyond critique to develop practical solutions to environmental and other problems.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They additionally advocate for professionalisation of the party organisation, and believe in maintaining a certain distance from social movements.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In Schily's case the development of his beliefs led him to leave the Greens for the SPD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other realos like Christa Vennegerts argued for clarification and development of policies in key areas such as economics and defence.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other Greens associated with the realo faction include Daniel Cohn-Bendit, Wolf-Dieter Hasenclever, Waltraud Schoppe, Rezzo Schlauch and Hubert Kleinert, as well as the thinktank the Institute for Social-Ecological Research.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to Parkin realos constituted the majority of party members and elected officials.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This group was particularly associated with Antje Vollmer and stressed a stronger concentration on ecological issues.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Michal Bondemann suggested that this faction reflected the development of a party bureaucracy, cadre and career politicians in the Greens.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In terms of the left-right spectrum, the left wing of the party was strengthened by an influx of radical left activists into the party when it was formed.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Whilst some contributed to the development of new perspectives through dialogue with environmental activists, others hewed closer to their pre-existing ideology whilst within the party, such as the Z Group which had originated as a breakaway from the Communist League.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Z Group was subject to a party tribunal in 1981 considering whether they should be expelled, which eventually decided against this.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Prominent figures in this group included Thomas Ebermann and Rainer Trampert.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Ebermann and Trampert were both leftists and fundis, as was Jutta Ditfurth.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Other more moderate eco-socialists were aligned with the realos on strategic questions.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This faction, officially established in 1984, opposed socialism and social security.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] These conflicts became less significant as the party moved toward the political mainstream in the 1990s.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This was mainly due to the weakening of the fundis leading to the realos establishing control of the party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 1988 accusations of financial irregularities within the party were made by the news magazine *Der Spiegel* and also by Cohn-Bendit.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Although an investigative commission rejected the claims in October, at party congress in Karlsruhe in December Ditfurth accused the realos of supplying false information to *Der Spiegel* in a speech which was poorly received by delegates.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The congress passed a motion of no confidence and the fundi controlled Federal Executive Committee resigned *en bloc*, resulting in the faction losing one of their biggest strongholds within the party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Realo control over the party was secured after its poor performance in the first federal election in the reunified Germany in 1990, when the West and East German Greens ran separately and the former failed to cross the electoral threshold and elected any Bundestag members.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Paul Hockenos has suggested that this period saw the end of the fundi-realo dimension of struggle within the party, although left-right contestation continued.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] After this period, the party moved away from pacifism, supporting EU military cooperation and military interventions in Yugoslavia and Afghanistan, and watered down its commitment to other non-environmental issues such as feminism and social justice.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 2021 federal election, the WZB Berlin Social Science Center classified the party as the most centrist of Germany's left-wing parties.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Annalena Baerbock campaigned from the left of the SPD, stating that the party's economic program is geared towards the "common good" while the SPD's no longer is.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has a more pragmatic approach to workers' rights than the SPD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] On the other hand, the party clearly holds positions to the left of the SPD on issues such as fiscal discipline, particularly on the debt brake, the climate transition, and property expropriation in Berlin.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They are focusing on environmentalist and socially progressive policies.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Emphasis is placed on mitigating climate change, reducing carbon emissions, and fostering sustainability and environmentally-friendly practices.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] They support equality, social justice, and humanitarian responses to events such as the European migrant crisis.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Their fiscal platform is flexible and seeks to balance social, economic, and environmental interests.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party is strongly pro-European, advocating European federalism, and promotes wider international cooperation, including strengthening existing alliances.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Starting from the leadership of Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck, commentators have observed the Greens taking a pragmatic, moderate approach to work with parties from across the political spectrum.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Baerbock described their stances and style as a form of "radical realism" attempting to reconcile principles with practical politics.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] At the same time, the party has denounced populism and division, and placed rhetorical emphasis on optimism and cross-party cooperation.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Accompanied by record high popularity and election results, this led some to suggest that the Greens were filling a gap in the political centre, which was left by the declining popularity of the CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has economically left-liberal views.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens are regarded as taking a Atlanticist line on defense and pushing for a stronger common EU foreign policy, especially against Russia and China.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Former Green Party co-leader Annalena Baerbock proposed a post-pacifist foreign policy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] She supports eastward expansion of NATO and has considered the number of UN resolutions critical of Israel as "absurd compared to resolutions against other states." The party's program included references to NATO as an "indispensable" part of European security.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have promised to abolish the contested Nord Stream 2 pipeline to ship Russian natural gas to Germany.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party criticized the EU's investment deal with China.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] It describes China as a "systematic rival", though the party also favors cooperation with China to fight climate change.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 2016, the Greens criticised Germany's defense plan with Saudi Arabia, which has been waging war in Yemen and has been accused of massive human rights violations.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party remains divided over issues such as nuclear disarmament and U.S. nuclear weapons on German territory.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Some Greens want Germany to sign the United Nations' Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Ever since the party's inception, The Greens have been concerned with the immediate halt of construction or operation of all nuclear power stations.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] As an alternative, they promote a shift to non-nuclear renewable energy and a comprehensive program of energy conservation.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In 1986, large parts of Germany were covered with radioactive contamination from the Chernobyl disaster and Germans went to great lengths to deal with the contamination.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Germany's anti-nuclear stance was strengthened.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] From the mid-1990s onwards, anti-nuclear protests were primarily directed against transports of radioactive waste in "CASTOR" containers.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] After the Chernobyl disaster, the Greens became more radicalised and resisted compromise on the nuclear issue.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 1990s, a re-orientation towards a moderate program occurred, with concern about global warming and ozone depletion taking a more prominent role.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the federal red-green government (1998–2005) many people became disappointed with what they saw as excessive compromise on key Greens policies.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The central idea of green politics is sustainable development.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The concept of environmental protection is the cornerstone of Alliance 90/The Greens policy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In particular, the economic, energy and transport policy claims are in close interaction with environmental considerations.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens acknowledge the natural environment as a high priority and animal protection should be enshrined as a national objective in constitutional law.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] An effective environmental policy would be based on a common environmental code, with the urgent integration of a climate change bill.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the red-green coalition (1998–2005) a policy of agricultural change was launched labeled as a paradigm shift in agricultural policy towards a more ecological friendly agriculture, which needs to continue.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have praised the European Green Deal, which aims to make the EU climate neutral by 2050.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Climate change is at the center of all policy considerations.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] This includes environmental policy and safety and social aspects.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The plans of the Alliance 90/The Greens provide a climate change bill laying down binding reductions to greenhouse gas emissions in Germany by 2020 restricting emissions to minus 40 percent compared to 1990.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Alliance 90/The Greens supports the eventual federalization of the European Union into a Federal European Republic (German: *Föderale Europäische Republik*), i.e. a single federal European sovereign state.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] A similarly high priority is given to transport policy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The switch from a traveling allowance to a mobility allowance, which is paid regardless of income to all employees, replacing company car privileges.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The truck toll will act as a climate protection instrument internalizing the external costs of transport.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Railway should be promoted in order to achieve the desired environmental objectives and the comprehensive care of customers.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The railway infrastructure is to remain permanently in the public sector, allowing a reduction in expenditure on road construction infrastructure.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens want to control privileges on kerosene and for international flights, introduce an air ticket levy.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Fossil fuels such as heavy oil or diesel shall be replaced by emission-neutral fuels and green propulsion systems in order to make shipping climate-neutral in the long term.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] For many years, the Green Party has advocated against the "Ehegattensplitting" policy, under which the incomes of married couples are split for taxation purposes.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In its 2013 platform, the Green Party successfully advocated for a minimum wage of 8.50 Euro per hour, which was implemented on 1 January 2015.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] It continues to press for higher minimum wages.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens want the starting retirement age to remain 67, but with some qualifications – for example, a provision for partial retirement.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party supports and has supported various forms of rent regulation.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] During the 2021 election, the party called for rent hikes to be capped at 2.5% per year.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens support progressive taxation and is critical of FDP efforts to cut taxes for top earners.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Green Party supports the implementation of quotas in executive boards, the policy of equal pay for equal work, and continuing the fight against domestic violence.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to its website, the Green Party "fights for the acceptance and against the exclusion of homosexuals, bisexuals, intersex- and transgender people and others".
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] In order to recognize the political persecution that LGBT+ people face abroad, the Green Party wants to extend asylum to LGBTQIA+ people abroad.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The policy change was sponsored primarily by Volker Beck, one of the Party's most prominent gay members.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Because of the extensive support the Green Party has given the LGBTQIA+ community since its conception, many LGBTQIA+ people vote for the Green Party even if their political ideology does not quite align otherwise.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party supports the legalization and regulation of cannabis and was the sponsor of the 2015 proposed iteration of the German cannabis control bill.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Furthermore, the Greens support research on the drug and the use of marijuana for medicinal purposes.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] A 2000 study by the Infratest Dimap political research company has suggested the Green voter demographic includes those on higher incomes (e.g. above €2,000/month) and the party's support is less among households with lower incomes.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The same polling research also concluded that the Greens received fewer votes from the unemployed and general working population, with business people favouring the party as well as the centre-right liberal Free Democratic Party.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] According to the Infratest Dimap political research company for the ARD, the Greens received more voters from the age group 34–42 than any other age group and that the young were generally more supportive of the party than the old.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The Greens have more support concentrated in metropolitan areas rather than rural areas, except for a small number of rural areas with critical local environmental concerns, such as strip mining or radioactive waste deposits.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The cities of Bonn, Cologne, Stuttgart, Berlin, Hamburg, Frankfurt and Munich have among the highest percentages of Green voters in the country.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] Large towns with Green mayors as of March 2026 include Hanover, Kassel, Munich and Münster.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alliance-90-the-greens-p02] The party has a lower level of support in the states of the former German Democratic Republic (East Germany); nonetheless, the party is currently represented in every state Landtag except Brandenburg, Saarland, and Thuringia.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Alois was born on 20 September 1933 at Zeil Castle near Leutkirch im Allgäu.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He was a son of Erich, 6th Prince of Waldburg-Zeil (1899–1953) and Princess Monika of Löwenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg (1905–1992).
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] His elder brother was Georg, 7th Prince of Waldburg-Zeil.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] He studied politics and economics at the University of Bonn, the Sapienza University of Rome, and the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Waldburg-Zeil was from 1980 to 1998 member of German Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] On 21 June 1956, he married Clarissa, Countess von Schönborn-Wiesentheid (b.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alois-graf-von-waldburg-zeil] Alois, Count von Waldburg-Zeil died on 14 December 2014.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In 1947, Brück joined the Socialist Youth of Germany – Falcons.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] He was regional president of the Falcons in Saarland from 1956 to 1967.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] He volunteered at *Saar-Volksstimme* from 1949 to 1951, and then worked as an editorial consultant until 1953.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In 1955, he began working at *Saarbrücker Allgemeine Zeitung*, where he became an assistant editor.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In 1952, Brück assisted in the foundation of the DSP, which did not reach Saarland until 1955.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In 1960, he became a member of the executive committee of the DSP in Saarland.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] From 1960 to 1973, Brück served as a member of the municipal council of his hometown, Heusweiler.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] From 1965 to 1990, he was a member of the Bundestag.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In the Bundestag, he was President of the Economic Cooperation Committee from 1969 to 1974.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In May 1974, he became Parliamentary State Secretary of the Economic Cooperation Committee under the appointment of Chancellor Helmut Schmidt.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] After the election of Helmut Kohl, Brück left the federal government in 1982.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] In 1987, Brück was elected to the Bundestag with 46.4% of the vote, representing Saarbrücken.
[src:alfred-mechtersheimer/alwin-brück] Brück died on 14 February 2020 at the age of 88.
